    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="189"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">President <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                        >Wilson</persName>’s Files</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Poincaré</persName> to
                        President <persName corresp="#p_WW1" type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 12, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.<note n="3" xml:id="d189fn3">Time of receipt not indicated.</note>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. President</hi>: I will not let the anniversary of
                        <persName corresp="#p_PGJJ1">General Pershing</persName>’s arrival in France
                    with the first contingents of the American Army pass by without expressing to
                    you my admiration for the magnificent effort successfully put forth since then
                    by the great sister republic and my warm congratulations on the splendid troops
                    who are beginning to give daily examples of their bravery on the battlefield.
                    The Allies, who have at present to hold in check forces largely increased by
                    Russia’s capitulation, are living through the most trying hours of the war; but
                    the speedy formation of new American units and the unceasing growth of ocean
                    transportation are bringing us surely nearer to the day when the balance will at
                    last be restored. When it is turned in our favor, the Allied armies in brotherly
                    union will wreak a decisive revenge on the enemy and by their common victory
                    will lay the foundations of a peace conforming to the principles solemnly set
                    forth by you and assuring, with the necessary guarantees, the rule of law and
                    the freedom of nations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Raymond Poincaré</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
